        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: The sensitivity is driven by the spectral lines. In order to study the detailed kinematics of the spectral lines, we will need 2 K rms (3.2mJy/beam), which will yield 10 sigma detections of optically-thin 20 K lines, and &gt;50 sigma on optically-thick 100-150 K lines.  Continuum self-calibration on the bright hot cores (peak intensities of 100 mJy/beam) should allow us to remove residual atmospheric and instrumental phase variations.  However, we note that the rms of the continuum images may not quite reach the theoretical value of ~0.03 mJy due to imaging dynamic range limitations.  In other words, the roughly 1.5 hours of uv-coverage may not quite reach the theoretical imaging dynamic range of 100/0.03 = 3333. But this will not impact the key science goals because the spectral line cubes which dictate our sensitivity requirement will not be limited in this manner, because of the larger noise in individual channels.  

Imaging: A single pointing effectively covers the area of interest.
All four of the known millimeter sources fit within the inner 1/3 of the primary beam.  The largest physical scale (the diameter of the known dust cores) is about 4 arcsec, and is within the largest angular scale recoverable at the required resolution of 0.2 arcsec which is needed to resolve the innermost accretion structures.

Correlator Setup: We will use one spectral window to obtain a deep
continuum image.  We have chosen a part of the Band 6 spectrum (centered at 223 GHz) which has a minimum of contamination of spectral lines as seen in the Sgr B2 line survey of Nummelin et al. (1998, ApJS, 117, 427).  In order to identify and avoid the few contaminating lines without unnecessarily sacrificing any continuum bandwidth, we will use an FDM window with 4-channel averaging to obtain 2.6 km/s resolution. We will use three higher resolution FDM windows to measure critical spectral lines in these spectacular hot cores.  We will observe the 12-11 and 13-12 ladders of CH3CN with two 468 MHz windows.  Line confusion is an issue in these hot cores, so by observing two ladders of CH3CN we will double the number of potential lines available to image the gas kinematics and to fit for gas temperature.  The CH3_13CN lines are covered in the same spectral windows, which will be useful in the directions of highest optical depth.   By centering on the 12-11 K=7 component, we will cover the K=0-10 components of CH3CN and the K=0..8 components of CH3_13CN, with at least 18 MHz to spare on both edges.  Similarly, for the 13-12 ladder, we will center on the K=6 component to cover the K=0-9 components with at least 28 MHz to spare, and the K=0-8 components of CH3_13CN.

In the fourth baseband, we will use four 58 MHz windows to observe nine additional lines which fit comfortably within the specified windows:
(1) HC3N 26-25 and HC3N v5=1 26-25
(2) HC3N v6= 26-25 and CH3OH-A- 14(1,13)-13(2,12)
(3) CH3OH-E 22(1,21)-22(0,22) and C2H5CN 25(3,23)-25(3,22)
(4) HC3N v7=2, 13CH3OH 5(1,4)-4(1,3),  ethylene glycol 24(2,23)-23(2,22)

Based on our lower angular resolution SMA data, all of these species show consistent velocity structure, and the typical line widths will be 3.5 km/s.  To measure the gas kinematics, we need ~10 resolution elements across the lines, thus requiring the FDM spectral windows, and &lt;=0.35 km/s resolution, as we have selected.
 
Calibration: We do not require any unusual calibration.

Scheduling contraints: none

Data rate: By using narrow windows and a strategic amount of spectral averaging, we have carefully selected our spectral window characteristics in order to achieve our science goals and yet still remain at 11 MB/sec, which is below the threshold for a high data rate.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
