            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: Our sensitivity requirement is based on the continuum and the need to search for faint hypercompact HII regions (n_e=1E7 cm-3, T=10000K) down to 5 AU in radius, which is just inside the tau=1 radius for a gravitationally-trapped HCHII region.  We model this HCHII region to have a flux density of 0.2 mJy at 97.5 GHz (using formulae of Beckert et al. 2000).  A 5-sigma detection requires 0.04 mJy/beam rms, achievable in about 32 minutes (including calibration overheads).  This will reach a sensitivity about two orders of magnitude better than the best existing image in this band from ATCA (Beuther et al. 2008) and with 6 times better angular resolution.  Therefore, even if this sensitivity is not reached, we will still gather excellent images of the known hot cores for detailed comparison to the Band 6 continuum image.

Imaging: A single pointing easily covers the area of interest.  The
largest physical scale of interest (the diameter of the known dust cores) is about 4 arcsec, and is within the largest angular scale recoverable at the required resolution of 0.4 arcsec. Any newly-detected HCHII regions will be more compact (1 arcsec or less)

Correlator Setup: To achieve our sensitivity goal in the least amount of telescope time, we will use the standard continuum setup with 4 TDM windows, all of which avoid atmospheric lines.  As we designed it, this setup also avoids most of the strong lines that these hot cores exhibit, including HCN, HCO+ and the CO isotopomers (see the SEST spectral line survey of Thorwirth et al. 2005, IAU 235, P115).  Due to the line-rich nature of the hot cores, there may still be some contamination from spectral lines that are not strong enough to be visible in a single TDM channel (and subsequently flagged).  We can check for this effect by comparing the images constructed from different portions of each spectral window and eliminating suspect channels.

Calibration: We do not require any unusual calibration.

Scheduling contraints: none

Data rate: This simple all-TDM experiment has a low data rate.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
